### 1. One-Line Summary
H3 Neo is a tacky, hard, stroke-driven Chinese rubber built for heavy spin and linear power, while Dynaryz CMD is a softer, bouncier modern rubber focused on easy speed, dwell, and allround-offense consistency.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:**
        * H3 Neo: Low passive rebound; short strokes and flat hits feel slower unless you accelerate through the sponge.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Noticeably higher free speed/catapult at low effort, making depth easier from compact swings.
    * **Top End:**
        * H3 Neo: Very high ceiling if you can compress the hard sponge; power scales with full-body acceleration.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Strong but more elastic top end; reaches fast earlier, but the ceiling is more sponge-catapult than pure stroke-driven.
    * **Linearity:**
        * H3 Neo: Highly linear—what you put in is what you get (great for repeatable power).
        * Dynaryz CMD: More nonlinear due to bounce sponge behavior; easier pace changes but less dead-straight linear.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:**
        * H3 Neo: Excellent at lifting backspin when you engage sponge + tack; demands good acceleration and contact quality.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Easier first loop with medium-soft sponge and grippy surface; less demanding timing/effort.
    * **Max Spin:**
        * H3 Neo: Among the best for heavy, loaded topspin when you hit hard and brush thin-to-thick properly.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Very high spin for a modern rubber, but the absolute heavy-ball tends to be less brutal than a fully engaged H3-style tacky hit.
    * **Topsheet Grip:**
        * H3 Neo: Tacky/adhesive topsheet emphasizes brush and serve spin; excels in slow spin creation.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Friction-focused Advanced Traction Surface style grip—more mechanical bite than tacky stick.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:**
        * H3 Neo: Typically lower to medium throw unless you really brush; produces a heavier, more direct arc.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Generally higher/safer arc from added dwell and catapult, especially on topspin rallies.
    * **Safety:**
        * H3 Neo: High safety when youre actively accelerating (ball dips hard), but punishes lazy contact.
        * Dynaryz CMD: More built-in safety at moderate effort; easier clearance over the net in real match tempo.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:**
        * H3 Neo: Firm, solid contact with clear feedback; can feel hard/boardy on soft strokes.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Softer, springier feel with a pronounced bounce/sound character.
    * **Dwell:**
        * H3 Neo: Dwell comes from tack + engaged sponge; short dwell if you dont compress it.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Naturally longer dwell from medium-soft sponge (notably forgiving).

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:**
        * H3 Neo: Lower catapult means less random bounce; good predictability, but very technique-dependent on spin read.
        * Dynaryz CMD: More reactive sponge can amplify incoming spin if touch is passive; rewards active, clean hands.
    * **Touch Play:**
        * H3 Neo: Strong for stop, push, and serve because it stays short and grabs the ball.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Very good touch for a modern rubber, but you must manage the catapult on drop shots.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:**
        * H3 Neo: Can be stable but often slow; passive blocks may sit up unless you close angle and add intent.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Easier passive block depth due to rebound; requires angle discipline because of bounce.
    * **Active Counter:**
        * H3 Neo: Excellent when you drive through the ball—very direct, heavy counter-topspin.
        * Dynaryz CMD: Quick countering is easy from compact strokes; excels for timing-based counter-loopers.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose H3 Neo if:**
    * You generate your own power (full-body acceleration) and want maximum heavy-ball topspin with a linear response.
    * You value a lower-catapulty short game for serve/receive and third-ball patterns.
    * You prefer a firmer, more connected feel and dont mind that it can feel slow on lazy strokes.

* **Choose Dynaryz CMD if:**
    * You want easier access to speed/spin from compact swings and more forgiveness under pressure.
    * You like a softer feel with longer dwell for opening, countering, and spin variation.
    * Your style mixes controlled topspin and allround offense, and you benefit from modern sponge rebound.